    ("L26", "A trade scene on the Silk Road circa 700 CE: a Central Asian merchant exchanges goods with a Byzantine merchant using gold solidi as payment. Both men in period Central Asian and Byzantine clothing respectively. The coins are inspected briefly and accepted. The Byzantine solidus circulating from England to China, accepted by people who share no language. Wide cinematic shot, Silk Road caravanserai setting."),
    ("L27", "A world map circa 800 CE showing the Byzantine solidus's circulation range: arrows from Constantinople spreading to England, Scandinavia, sub-Saharan Africa, Persia, India, and China. The coin has reached the known world. The Byzantine monetary zone is larger than the Byzantine military zone. Gold map lines on dark background, cinematic documentary style."),
    ("L28", "The medieval city of Florence circa 1252: a prosperous Italian city with stone towers, merchant districts, the Arno River visible in the background. The city is wealthy and commercially active. Citizens in richly colored Italian medieval clothing — wool surcoats, leather belts, layered robes — move through the streets. A mint building visible with its official seal above the door. Cinematic wide establishing shot, warm Mediterranean midday light."),
    ("L29", "The first Florentine florin being struck: a Florentine mint worker places a gold blank on an anvil and strikes it with a die bearing the lily of Florence on one side and John the Baptist on the other. The coin emerges perfectly round, precisely struck. Three and a half grams of twenty-four carat gold. A new monetary standard born in 1252. Cinematic close-medium shot, mint workshop, warm forge light."),
    ("L30", "The Florentine gold florin coin: extreme close-up on black velvet. Obverse: the lily of Florence, clean and stylized. Reverse: John the Baptist standing, holding a staff. The gold is brilliant and pure, the strike clean. This coin will not change for 281 years. Museum macro photography, warm amber studio lighting."),
    ("L31", "A Florentine banker in the 1300s — a prosperous man in richly colored wool robes and a leather belt with account books — at a large counting table covered in gold florin coins. He counts and sorts them. Behind him, open shelves of ledger books and locked strongboxes. The florin is the basis of international finance across Europe and the Mediterranean. Cinematic wide shot, Florentine banking house interior, warm lamp light."),
    ("L32", "A merchant scene in late 14th-century Florence during the Black Death: a merchant in traveling robes arrives at a foreign trading post and presents a gold florin in payment. Despite the chaos of the plague visible in the background — people in masks, shuttered windows — the florin is accepted without hesitation. Monetary discipline persisting through catastrophe. Cinematic medium shot, late medieval European architecture, overcast light."),
    ("L33", "A 15th-century Florentine marketplace with merchants from multiple nations — Flemish cloth merchants in northern wool coats, Venetian merchants in colorful Italian robes, Ottoman merchants in turbans and silk — all conducting transactions with gold florins as the common medium. Multiple languages, one coin. Cinematic wide shot, bustling international market, warm afternoon light."),
    ("L34", "A Florentine mint official, 1280s, in formal city robes, signing a certification document guaranteeing the purity of a new batch of florins. The document carries the official seal of the Florentine Republic. The institutional backing of a republican government rather than a personal ruler. Cinematic medium shot, official interior, warm document lamp."),
    ("L35", "The Florentine Republic in political crisis circa 1530: armed men in the streets of Florence, the Medici returning to power, the republican government collapsing. A mint official at his desk looking at the incoming orders — the coin specifications are about to change. The moment when republican governance ends and monetary discipline ends with it. Cinematic wide shot, chaotic street scene visible through window, interior tension."),
    ("L36", "The last Florentine florin of the original specification: a coin being examined by a mint master in 1533 with an expression of resignation. This is the final coin minted to the 281-year standard. On his desk, new specifications from the Medici court that will alter the formula. The end of the longest unbroken monetary standard in European history. Cinematic close-medium shot, Florentine mint, late afternoon window light."),
    ("L37", "A long corridor in a medieval trading city — Constantinople or Alexandria — lined with merchants conducting business. Every transaction uses gold solidi. The trust that makes the corridor hum with commerce is invisible but total. When the emperor maintains the coin's integrity, armies stay loyal and trade expands. Cinematic wide tracking perspective, Byzantine architecture, warm torchlight and daylight."),
    ("L38", "A historical scene of Byzantine coinage debasement beginning in the 1040s CE: a mint official looking with discomfort at new imperial orders reducing gold content in the solidus. He holds a slightly yellowish debased coin beside a pure gold original. The faces on both coins are the same emperor. The trust that took seven centuries to build is beginning to crack. Cinematic close medium shot, Byzantine mint interior."),
    ("L39", "A wide aerial view of the ancient city of Sardis in western Turkey today: the archaeological ruins visible on a dry hillside, the Pactolus River still running through the valley below, smaller and quieter than in ancient times. Tourist signs mark the ancient mint site. The place where the stamp was first invented, still identifiable in the landscape six centuries after Christ. Cinematic documentary aerial photography, warm afternoon light, deep sense of historical continuity."),

    # ── s4_potosi (P01–P34) ──
    # Narration: Cerro Rico discovery 1545, the mountain's size, mita conscription,
    # workers descending Monday with candles, week-long shift, carrying 300-pound ore,
    # mercury at Huancavelica, barefoot treading, the hospital, death toll,
    # silver shipped to Spain, the Price Revolution, bread prices, Spain's bankruptcies,
    # Dutch/English/Chinese merchants receiving Spanish money.

    ("P01", "A wide establishing shot of the Bolivian altiplano circa 1545: vast high-altitude grassland at nearly 14,000 feet elevation, thin cloud wisps, brown-gold grass stretching to the horizon. In the middle distance, the unmistakable conical peak of Cerro Rico rises sharply above the plain — a perfectly symmetrical mountain of reddish-brown rock. The landscape is immense and austere. A small group of Spanish prospectors on horseback visible in the foreground as tiny figures. Cinematic ultra-wide shot, cold high-altitude Andean light."),
    ("P02", "A closer view of Cerro Rico, the Rich Mountain, at its full imposing scale: the conical peak fills the upper half of the frame, its reddish-brown flanks streaked with silver ore veins visible as lighter diagonal bands. The sky above is the deep blue of high altitude. At the base, a small indigenous settlement. The mountain's enormity communicates that this is the largest silver deposit ever found. Cinematic wide shot, cold blue-sky Andean light."),
    ("P03", "Spanish colonial administrators in doublets and breeches standing before Cerro Rico with indigenous guides in Andean dress, gesturing at the mountain's flanks. Maps and documents in hand. The expression on the Spanish faces ranges from astonishment to greed. A Spanish official writes in a ledger. The discovery moment in its administrative reality — not dramatic discovery but systematic claim-taking. Cinematic wide shot, cold Andean midday light."),
    ("P04", "The colonial city of Potosi circa 1600 at its height, viewed from above: a dense grid of Spanish colonial buildings at the base of Cerro Rico, thousands of structures, smoke from refining operations, the mountain dominating everything. The city is one of the largest in the world at this moment — 160,000 people. The mountain of silver has built a colonial city overnight. Cinematic aerial historical illustration, early morning mountain light."),
    ("P05", "A Spanish colonial official reading the mita decree to a gathered crowd of indigenous Andean men in a plaza, circa 1560. The men are in traditional Andean clothing — wool tunics, woven sandals — standing in organized rows. One in seven will be conscripted. A scribe records names. The faces in the crowd show the range from resignation to fear. Cinematic wide shot, colonial plaza architecture, harsh midday mountain light."),
    ("P06", "Indigenous Andean men leaving their home village for the mita, circa 1580. A column of men in traditional Andean clothing — wool ponchos, woven ch'ullus, leather sandals — walking along a mountain path toward Potosi. Their families stand at the village edge watching. The men carry small bundles. Some look back once. Cinematic wide shot, Andean mountain landscape, gray morning light, emotionally heavy."),
    ("P07", "A Monday morning at the entrance to Cerro Rico's mine shafts, circa 1590: a line of indigenous mitayo workers in rough Andean clothing preparing to descend. Each man has a small tallow candle tied to his forehead with a cloth band, the only light source they will have. The shaft entrance is a stone-framed hole in the mountain. Thirteen thousand men per year entering this darkness. Cinematic wide shot, cold dawn light, the mountain visible above."),
    ("P08", "Close-up of an indigenous mitayo worker's face at the mine entrance, circa 1590. He wears a rough wool tunic and the tallow candle on his forehead — a thin flame in the cold dawn air. His expression is closed and interior, a man preparing himself. Behind him, the darkness of the shaft. The candle flame is the only warmth in the frame. Cinematic close portrait, dramatic chiaroscuro, cold exterior light meeting warm candle glow."),
    ("P09", "Inside the Cerro Rico mine shaft: an indigenous worker in rough wool clothing descends a rough-hewn wooden ladder into darkness, his candle casting a small circle of warm light on the dark rock walls around him. The shaft goes straight down into blackness below. The walls are close. The temperature is cold and getting colder. Cinematic shot looking down the shaft past the worker, extreme chiaroscuro."),
    ("P10", "Deep inside Cerro Rico: a horizontal gallery 600 feet underground, temperature swinging between extreme cold at depth and warmth from the miners' bodies. An indigenous worker in rough Andean clothing uses an iron pick to break silver-bearing ore from the rock face by candlelight. The rock sparkles with embedded silver ore. The only light is his single candle. Cinematic medium close-up, total darkness except the candle, the ore glittering."),
    ("P11", "An indigenous mitayo worker carrying a massive load of silver ore on his back up a rough wooden ladder inside the mine shaft. He wears a rough wool tunic and leather sandals. The load is secured in a large leather ore bag on his back — an estimated 300 pounds. His muscles strain visibly. He cannot straighten fully in the low shaft. By candlelight, hundreds of feet below the surface. Cinematic close-medium shot, extreme chiaroscuro, the physical weight of the labor the visual subject."),
    ("P12", "A wide shot looking up a Potosi mine shaft from below: a series of rough wooden ladders ascending through rock into a small circle of daylight far above. An indigenous worker is visible midway up, the ore bag on his back making him a dark silhouette against the rock. Other workers are visible on ladders above and below. The vertical labor chain — ore moving from deep in the earth toward surface — made physical. Cinematic upward perspective, dramatic light-dark contrast."),
    ("P13", "The surface of Cerro Rico circa 1585: ore being unloaded from workers' backs at the surface into processing areas. Spanish overseers in period doublets and boots observe and record the quantities. Indigenous workers set down their loads with visible exhaustion before turning to go back down. The physical scale of the extraction — thousands of workers, continuous — visible in the organized chaos. Cinematic wide shot, mountain background, cold afternoon light."),
    ("P14", "The mercury amalgamation patio at Potosi circa 1580: a large stone courtyard where indigenous workers in rough Andean clothing mix silver ore with mercury in the grey, heavy amalgamation process. Workers move slowly through the thick mixture. The mercury is grey and heavy-looking. Spanish overseers in doublets observe from the edges. The scale is industrial for its era. Cinematic wide shot, overcast light, the heaviness of the labor palpable."),
    ("P15", "A map showing the distance between Potosi and Huancavelica: illustrated as a period-style map of colonial Peru and Bolivia, a thick arrow showing the 700-mile overland route from Huancavelica's mercury mines to Potosi's silver processing. The distance — nearly the length of California — traveled by mule caravans carrying liquid mercury in sealed clay jars. Documentary map illustration, aged parchment style, period cartography."),
    ("P16", "The Huancavelica mercury mine interior, circa 1580: workers in rough Andean wool clothing process cinnabar ore in a stone processing room. One worker is barefoot, walking through ore mixture saturated with mercury spread across a stone floor, his feet visible as he treads the mixture. Mercury vapors visible as wisps near the heated processing areas. Dramatic torchlight through rock openings, cinematic historical illustration."),
    ("P17", "Close-up of an indigenous worker's bare feet at Huancavelica, walking through a grey mercury-ore mixture. The skin of the feet and lower legs appears affected — slightly discolored — the beginning of mercury absorption through skin contact. The worker's feet are shown against the grey metallic surface of the ore mixture. The image is quiet and devastating. Cinematic extreme close-up, low light, photorealistic historical illustration."),
    ("P18", "The hospital at Huancavelica, circa 1590: a colonial Spanish stone building near the mine, set apart from the processing areas. Inside, a long hall with simple wooden cots, indigenous workers in various stages of mercury poisoning — tremors visible in some, others deeply ill. Spanish medical workers in dark wool clothing move between them. The hospital exists so workers can recover enough to return. Cinematic wide shot, interior, low window light."),
    ("P19", "The death toll made human: a row of simple crosses on a hillside above Potosi, extending to the horizon. Hundreds, then thousands of crosses visible. The high altitude sky is heavy with clouds. The crosses are rough and unadorned — not memorials but markers, the administrative record of the system that killed its workers as a matter of operating procedure. Cinematic wide shot, gray Andean light, the scale of the crosses the visual argument."),
    ("P20", "A wide demographic illustration: a map of the Andean region circa 1600 showing indigenous population collapse. Dark areas representing population density fading into lighter shades across the region — from disease, displacement, forced labor, and mercury poisoning combined. The total scale of collapse visible as a geographic transformation. Documentary infographic style on dark background, deeply serious tone."),
    ("P21", "Silver ingots being loaded onto mule trains at the base of Cerro Rico for the journey to the coast, circa 1600. Large rectangular silver bars stacked in wooden frames on the backs of mules, a long caravan stretching back toward the mountain. Spanish guards in period military dress escort the silver. The beginning of its journey from Bolivia to Seville. Cinematic wide shot, cold Andean mountain light, the scale of the silver flow visible."),
    ("P22", "A Spanish treasure galleon in the port of Seville circa 1590, being unloaded. Silver ingots are carried on wooden pallets from ship to dock by workers in period Spanish clothing, supervised by Treasury officials in formal doublets. The dock is busy and organized. Behind the galleon, other ships with similar cargo. Twenty-five thousand tons of silver over fifty years. Cinematic wide shot, warm Mediterranean harbor light."),
    ("P23", "An illustrated graph of the Price Revolution: a simple line chart showing bread prices in Western Europe from 1500 to 1620, starting flat and then rising steeply — three to six times — in the century following 1550. The line is drawn in gold on aged parchment, the rise unmistakable. Period-appropriate infographic illustration style, warm tones."),
    ("P24", "A Spanish market scene circa 1580: a bread stall in a Spanish town. A woman in period Spanish dress points at the price board with an expression of shock and complaint. The price is higher than last month, higher than last year. The baker in his apron gestures helplessly — he pays more for flour now too. The Price Revolution as experienced by ordinary people, street level. Cinematic medium shot, Spanish market architecture, warm afternoon light."),
    ("P25", "An allegorical image of quantitative easing as flood: silver coins pouring from the top of the frame into a European market scene below, coins piling up in the streets, merchants unable to pick them up fast enough. Prices float upward on small signs. The silver is arriving faster than the economy can absorb it. Cinematic documentary illustration, bright Spanish market, the abundance that destroys rather than enriches."),
    ("P26", "The Spanish royal court circa 1557, the moment of the first bankruptcy declaration: Philip II of Spain in formal Spanish royal dress — black doublet, ruff collar, Habsburg jaw — seated at a desk signing a bankruptcy decree. His treasurer stands behind him with papers. The king who owns the world's largest silver mine cannot pay his debts. Cinematic wide portrait shot, dark Spanish royal interior, candlelight."),
    ("P27", "A timeline graphic showing Spain's three bankruptcies: 1557, 1575, 1596 — three bold markers on a horizontal timeline spanning 1550 to 1600. Each marker has a small illustration of silver flowing into Spain from one side and immediately out the other side. The visual argument: the silver flowed through, not to Spain. Clean cinematic documentary graphic on dark background."),
    ("P28", "Spanish domestic manufacturing in collapse, circa 1580: an empty Spanish textile workshop that was once busy. Looms stand idle, workers gone. Through the window, a street where goods are being purchased from a Flemish merchant's cart rather than made locally. The Spanish goods are too expensive — inflation made by the silver flood has priced them out of their own market. Cinematic wide shot, dark interior versus bright street."),
    ("P29", "A Dutch merchant in Amsterdam circa 1590 receiving a chest of Spanish silver coins in payment for a shipment of fine cloth. He opens the chest, examines the coins with satisfaction, records the transaction in his ledger. The silver that was mined by indigenous workers at Potosi is now in Amsterdam, having traveled through Spain without stopping. Cinematic medium shot, Dutch mercantile interior, gray northern light."),
    ("P30", "An English merchant ship in the English Channel circa 1590, loaded with wool cloth and manufactured goods headed for Spanish ports. The English captain reviews his accounts — the Spanish are paying in silver for goods they can no longer produce themselves. English merchants are growing rich on Spanish silver while Spain's manufacturing collapses. Cinematic wide shot, gray English Channel light, period-accurate ship."),
    ("P31", "A Chinese merchant in late Ming Dynasty Canton, circa 1590, receiving a large payment of Spanish silver pieces of eight from a Manila Galleon trading partner. He weighs them on a precision scale and accepts them. China is demanding silver for silk and porcelain. The silver mined in Bolivia by indigenous workers is circling the globe. Cinematic medium shot, Chinese harbor setting, Ming dynasty clothing."),
    ("P32", "A conceptual global trade route map: silver flows from Cerro Rico in Bolivia eastward across the Atlantic to Seville, then north to Dutch and English merchants, and simultaneously westward across the Pacific via Manila Galleon to China. The mountain in Bolivia is the source of the world's first global monetary circulation. Cinematic documentary map on dark background, silver-white route lines."),
    ("P33", "The moral arithmetic made visual: a split image. Left panel shows an indigenous Potosi worker at the mine entrance — he dug the silver and received nothing. Center panel shows the Spanish crown — they owned the mountain and went bankrupt three times. Right panel shows a Dutch merchant counting silver coins in Amsterdam — he received the silver and built lasting wealth. Three outcomes from one mountain. Cinematic triptych, historically accurate period dress throughout."),
    ("P34", "Cerro Rico from above, in the present day: an aerial photograph of the mountain showing centuries of mining have hollowed and scarred the summit. The distinctive conical shape remains but the top is irregular and damaged from extraction. The colonial city of Potosi is visible below. The mountain that changed the price of everything on Earth is still there, still being mined, still visibly consumed. Cinematic aerial photography, cold modern Andean light."),

    # ── s5_gold_standard (G01–G41) ──
    # Narration: deflation mechanism, 1890s farmer, wheat prices falling, debt staying fixed,
    # creditors prospering, Bryan's Cross of Gold speech, convention erupting,
    # WWI suspending gold, post-war restoration, Keynes warning, Great Depression,
    # bank failures, governments unable to act, Sweden recovering, France suffering,
    # the correlation chart — countries that left gold first recovered first.

    ("G01", "A diagrammatic illustration of the gold standard mechanism: a government vault filled with gold bars connected by a line to a stack of paper banknotes. A label reads 'money supply limited by gold held.' An arrow shows that when gold drains out, the money supply contracts. The diagram is designed in the style of a 1900s economics textbook illustration, clean and clear on aged paper background."),
    ("G02", "The deflation mechanism illustrated: a falling price graph on the left, a fixed mortgage document on the right, the gap between them growing wider as the price falls further from the fixed debt number. The graph is drawn as a 1890s-style chart. The document is formal with official seals. The visual argument: the debt stays fixed while income falls. Period documentary infographic style."),
    ("G03", "An American Midwest wheat farm in 1890: a vast flat landscape with golden wheat fields stretching to the horizon under a big sky. A weathered farmhouse and barn in the middle distance. A farmer in worn period work clothes — denim overalls, flannel shirt, brimmed hat — stands at the edge of his field. The farm looks productive but the farmer's posture carries quiet anxiety. Cinematic wide shot, warm late-afternoon prairie light, photorealistic historical scene."),
    ("G04", "The 1890s American farmer at a bank window: he slides a mortgage document across the counter to a bank teller in a suit. The document shows one thousand dollars. The farmer holds a small bag of wheat-sale coins — clearly not enough. The teller's expression is bureaucratically neutral. This is a normal transaction; the abnormality is invisible in the numbers. Cinematic medium shot, period American bank interior, warm lamp light."),
    ("G05", "The wheat price collapse illustrated: a 1890s-style commodity price board in a grain elevator office showing wheat at fifty cents per bushel. A farmer stares at it. On the wall behind him, an old price board from 1885 showing one dollar per bushel is still faintly visible, now marked over. The prices are the whole story. Cinematic medium shot, grain elevator interior, period American setting."),
    ("G06", "A farmer doing the math at his kitchen table at night: a candle-lit table with a loan document showing one thousand dollars, and beside it a price chart showing wheat at fifty cents. He has pencil and paper. His arithmetic shows that he needs to sell two thousand bushels now to pay the same debt that one thousand bushels would have covered five years ago. His expression is the expression of a man who has just confirmed what he feared. Cinematic close-medium shot, farmhouse kitchen, candlelight."),
    ("G07", "A creditor in a well-appointed 1890s office — dark wood paneling, leather chairs, framed portraits — reviewing his bond portfolio. His expression is satisfied. The bonds are backed by gold, the dollar is stable, every cent he is owed will come back in full purchasing power. The gold standard works perfectly from where he sits. Cinematic wide shot, prosperous 1890s financial interior, afternoon window light."),
    ("G08", "A symbolic comparison: a scale with a gold coin on one side and a small bundle of wheat on the other. The gold side does not move. The wheat side rises and falls with the market. The debt is denominated in gold. The farmer's income comes from wheat. The asymmetry is the mechanism. Cinematic still life, dark background, dramatic side lighting on the scale."),
    ("G09", "The 1896 Democratic National Convention in Chicago: a vast convention hall packed with thousands of delegates in period frock coats and top hats. The hall is lit by gas lights and afternoon sun through high windows. The crowd is visibly energized and loud. On the stage, a young man — William Jennings Bryan — approaches the podium. The hall's scale communicates the size of the political moment. Cinematic wide shot, historical convention atmosphere."),
    ("G10", "William Jennings Bryan at the podium, mid-speech at the 1896 Democratic National Convention. He is 36, athletic, in a black frock coat. His right arm is outstretched toward the crowd, his expression fierce and committed. He has been practicing these lines for years. The crowd in front of him is rapt. Gas lights and summer afternoon light. Cinematic portrait-wide shot, period American convention hall."),
    ("G11", "The climactic moment of Bryan's speech: his arms stretched wide, a cross-like posture, delivering the line 'you shall not crucify mankind upon a cross of gold.' His face carries the conviction of someone who believes every word. The crowd in the hall is exploding — mouths open, arms raised. Hats and canes visible in the air. Cinematic dramatic wide shot, the hall erupting around him."),
    ("G12", "The crowd eruption after Bryan's speech: delegates in period frock coats and hats throwing their hats and canes into the air simultaneously, the hall a chaos of celebration. Some men are lifted onto shoulders. The noise is visible in the open mouths. Bryan stands at the podium looking at the eruption he has caused. Cinematic wide shot, convention hall, the physical energy of a political moment."),
    ("G13", "A wide panoramic view of the 1890s American Midwest: multiple farms visible across a flat landscape, the farmhouses small against the vast sky. On the horizon, the grain elevator of a small town. The landscape looks prosperous to the eye, but the invisible burden of fixed debt against falling grain prices is carried by every family in every farmhouse visible. Cinematic ultra-wide shot, warm prairie light."),
    ("G14", "Bryan's defeat in the 1896 election: a newspaper headline in period typography reading 'McKINLEY WINS — GOLD STANDARD PRESERVED.' The newspaper is held by a farmer in overalls, reading it outside a feed store. His face shows quiet resignation. The gold standard survived. Cinematic medium shot, period American small town exterior, gray autumn light."),
    ("G15", "World War One mobilization, August 1914: European soldiers in period military uniforms marching through city streets amid crowds of civilians. The scene is energetic and chaotic. In a government building window visible in the background, officials with papers are visible — the suspension of gold convertibility being ordered. The war requires money beyond what any gold reserve can provide. Cinematic wide shot, European city, period architecture and clothing."),
    ("G16", "A European central bank official, August 1914, posting a notice on the bank's exterior door: 'Gold payments suspended until further notice.' A small crowd of civilians reads the notice. Some look alarmed; others nod as if they expected it. The gold standard suspended not because anyone chose to but because war made it impossible. Cinematic medium shot, European bank exterior, period architecture, anxious crowd."),
    ("G17", "A documentary graphic showing WWI military spending: a bar chart showing that war spending required twelve times what peacetime taxation could provide. The bars are labeled with period-appropriate data. The visual argument: no gold-backed currency system can accommodate industrial warfare. Clean period-style infographic, sepia and dark tones."),
    ("G18", "The Bank of England exterior, 1925: the neoclassical facade on Threadneedle Street, a formal institution. An official announcement board on the door states the return to gold. City of London merchants and bankers pass in period business dress — dark coats, bowler hats. The restoration of the prewar exchange rate, a decision Keynes called catastrophic, happening in bureaucratic silence. Cinematic wide shot, London gray sky, period atmosphere."),
    ("G19", "John Maynard Keynes, circa 1925, at his desk in Cambridge or London: a lean intellectual in period three-piece suit, writing urgently. His expression is troubled and certain simultaneously. On the desk, papers with the title visible suggesting his 'Economic Consequences' arguments. He is writing that Britain's return to the prewar gold rate will deliver a decade of stagnation. Cinematic medium portrait, warm study lamp, dark wood office."),
    ("G20", "British export goods sitting unsold at a Liverpool dock, circa 1927: crates of manufactured goods — textiles, machinery — marked for export but not loaded. A shipping agent consults papers with a concerned expression. The overvalued pound has made British exports too expensive. The stagnation Keynes predicted is visible in the idle crates. Cinematic wide shot, gray northern English harbor, overcast light."),
    ("G21", "An American city street, 1930, showing a bank run: a large crowd of people in overcoats and hats pressing toward the doors of a bank. The doors are being held partially closed from inside. People at the front press against them. Panic visible in faces. The natural economic response to a crisis — trying to get your money out — threatening to accelerate the crisis. Cinematic wide shot, period American city architecture, gray depression-era sky."),
    ("G22", "Inside a 1930 bank during a run: a teller behind a wooden counter facing a growing line of anxious depositors demanding their money. The teller's expression is strained. Behind him, the bank manager with a phone to his ear. In the vault visible through a door, limited reserves. The gold standard means the bank cannot create money to stop the run. Cinematic medium wide shot, period American bank interior."),
    ("G23", "A documentary graphic showing the gold standard constraint during the Depression: a diagram with 'gold reserve' as the fixed ceiling and 'money supply' as a line that cannot exceed it. An arrow shows the need for more money to stop bank runs, but the ceiling is immovable. Governments watching banks fail while legally unable to act. Clean period infographic style."),
    ("G24", "A Federal Reserve official, circa 1931, at his desk reviewing the falling gold reserves. Documents show gold outflows. He picks up the phone to call a colleague — but there is nothing he can authorize. The gold standard forbids him to act. The contraction feeds itself. Cinematic close-medium shot, 1930s government office, window light."),
    ("G25", "The Great Depression's human toll: a breadline in an American city in 1932. Men in worn overcoats, hats, and work clothes stand in a long line extending around a corner and down the street. An urban soup kitchen distributes bread at the front. The sky is gray. The men are silent. Cinematic wide shot, period American city, gray winter depression-era light."),
    ("G26", "Sweden, 1931: a Swedish government official and finance minister in period dress reviewing documents at a conference table. One document is the formal announcement of Sweden leaving the gold standard. The official signs it. Sweden will be among the first to recover. Cinematic medium shot, formal Scandinavian government interior, neutral window light."),
    ("G27", "Sweden, 1935: a Swedish industrial factory in full operation — machinery running, workers in period work clothes busy on the floor, production active. Industrial production has climbed 14 percent above 1929 levels. The contrast to the depression visible elsewhere is the visual argument. Cinematic wide shot, Swedish factory interior, warm industrial light."),
    ("G28", "France, 1935: a closed French factory, machinery idle, workers standing outside a locked gate. A sign notes suspended operations. France is holding on to gold while Sweden is recovering. Industrial production is 26 percent below 1929 levels. The same story as Sweden, the opposite outcome. Cinematic wide shot, French industrial exterior, overcast northern French light."),
    ("G29", "French political scene, circa 1935: politicians and economists in formal period dress arguing in an ornate government chamber. Charts showing economic decline are on the table. France refuses to leave the gold standard. The argument for monetary orthodoxy against clear evidence of failure. Cinematic wide shot, French government interior, warm chamber light."),
    ("G30", "France, 1936: finally leaving the gold standard. An official at a press conference surrounded by journalists announces the decision. The announcement comes five years later than Sweden's. By then, French industry has been devastated. Cinematic medium shot, press conference setting, flash photography light."),
    ("G31", "A documentary correlation chart: a bar graph showing year of gold standard exit on the horizontal axis and year economic recovery began on the vertical axis for ten major economies. The correlation is perfect — every country that left gold first recovered first, without exception. The graph is dramatic in its clarity. Clean cinematic documentary graphic on dark background, gold accent color."),
    ("G32", "A symbolic image of the gold standard's inflexibility: a steel mechanical system — gears, levers, a rigid frame — with an economic crisis represented as a growing external pressure pushing against it. The mechanism cannot flex. The pressure builds. The system is strong but brittle. Cinematic industrial metaphor illustration, dark background, dramatic mechanical lighting."),
    ("G33", "The 1890s American farmer one more time, but now surrounded by a wider economic landscape: his farm visible, the bank in the distance, the grain elevator, the road to market. The entire system of creditors, debtors, wheat prices, and fixed mortgages visible as a landscape. He stands in the center — not a victim of bad luck but a victim of the system's design. Cinematic wide establishing shot, warm late-afternoon prairie light."),
    ("G34", "A wide view of the global economy circa 1936: a map showing all major economies color-coded — those that have left the gold standard and are recovering are shown in warm gold tones; those still on gold are shown in cold gray. The map is almost entirely warm gold by 1936. France is one of the last cold gray holdouts. Documentary map graphic, cinematic dark background."),
    ("G35", "The gold standard's final European failure visualized: a newspaper front page circa 1936 with headlines about the last European countries abandoning gold. The paper is surrounded by the debris of six years of depression — other headlines about bank failures, unemployment, production declines. The gold standard did not fail because of bad management. It failed because its core feature — inability to expand money — made crises into depressions. Cinematic archival document style."),
    ("G36", "A contemplative final image for this section: a large gold bar sitting behind metal bars in a bank vault, circa 1935. Through the vault bars, the gold gleams. But on the other side of those bars, the economy has contracted, farms have failed, factories have closed. The gold is intact, preserved, uncorrupted. And it is killing the economy. Cinematic wide shot, dramatic vault lighting, the gold bar as symbol of inflexibility."),
    ("G37", "A creditor of the 1890s in his library — dark wood paneling, a fire in the grate, leather-bound books. He sits comfortably reviewing his bond portfolio. The gold standard has protected every cent of his wealth, inflation-proof. His comfort is the system working exactly as designed for one class of people. Cinematic wide shot, warm firelight, the ease of the creditor's position the visual subject."),
    ("G38", "A period-style political cartoon of the era: a giant golden cross dominating a landscape, and tiny farming figures pinned across its horizontal arms. Bryan's imagery made literal. The cross is immovable and gleaming; the figures below are struggling. The cartoon is rendered in a 1890s American newspaper illustration style, sepia and black ink, editorial force."),
    ("G39", "A 1930s American family sitting around a kitchen table in a farmhouse, the atmosphere heavy. A bank notice of foreclosure is on the table. The farmer's hands are clasped. His wife looks out the window. Their teenage son is looking at the notice. The gold standard worked perfectly for those who held debt. It destroyed those who owed it. Cinematic medium wide shot, farmhouse kitchen, harsh Depression-era light through window."),
    ("G40", "The Great Depression's end approaching, 1937: an American factory coming back to life — machinery being started, workers returning to the floor, supervisors checking equipment. The US has left the gold standard in 1933. Recovery is underway. The visual contrast to the idle factories of 1932 is the argument. Cinematic wide shot, American factory interior, warm industrial light of recovery."),
    ("G41", "A final summary graphic for the gold standard section: three side-by-side columns labeled 'Creditors' (protected, stable, prosperous), 'Debtors' (crushed by deflation, real debt doubled), and 'The System' (worked as designed — protected those who held debt). The visual argument that the gold standard was not neutral, it was designed with beneficiaries. Clean cinematic documentary infographic, dark background."),

    # ── s6_nixon (N01–N28) ──
    # Narration: Camp David August 1971, 15 advisers, communications blackout,
    # Volcker's legal pad, Britain's gold request, de Gaulle shipping gold to Paris,
    # Fort Knox depleted, Connally's bold advice, Nixon's televised speech,
    # "our currency your problem", announced as temporary, currencies floating,
    # Kissinger in Saudi Arabia, the petrodollar deal, OPEC pricing in dollars.

    ("N01", "The Camp David presidential retreat in Maryland, late summer 1971: the compound's main lodge building seen from outside, surrounded by mature trees in full late-summer foliage. Evening is approaching. The compound looks quiet from outside — no indication of the historic meeting about to happen inside. Cinematic wide establishing shot, warm late-afternoon August light filtering through trees, photorealistic."),
    ("N02", "August 13, 1971 — senior advisers arriving at Camp David: men in period suits and open collars stepping from cars in the compound parking area. An aide checks names against a list at the entrance. Fifteen senior advisers gathering for a secret weekend meeting. The communications blackout has already been ordered — no phones visible being used. Cinematic wide shot, late summer Camp David grounds."),
    ("N03", "Inside Camp David's main conference room, evening of August 13, 1971: fifteen senior advisers in period business attire seated around a large wooden conference table. Nixon stands at the head. The room is serious and close. No windows visible from the outside world. The expression on the faces ranges from grim determination to visible concern. Period-accurate Camp David interior, warm lamp light."),
    ("N04", "A visual of the communications blackout: a telephone switchboard operator in the Camp David communications room receiving orders — all outgoing calls blocked, incoming calls diverted. The red 'blackout' notice visible on the board. No advance notice to allies, no warning to the Federal Reserve or the IMF. The deliberate isolation of the decision. Cinematic close-medium shot, 1971 communications equipment."),
    ("N05", "Paul Volcker at the conference table, a tall thin man in a 1971 business suit, writing options on a large yellow legal pad. The pad is the center of the shot. His handwriting is clear and deliberate. Options listed in numbered format. Behind him on the wall, a large chart showing US gold reserves declining and dollar claims rising. The math that makes waiting any longer dangerous. Cinematic close-medium shot, Camp David conference room, evening."),
    ("N06", "A close-up of the yellow legal pad: Volcker's hand writes three options in clear cursive. The top option is underlined. The label 'CLOSE GOLD WINDOW' visible among the words. Other notes about import surcharges and wage controls visible. The pad as the artifact of a historic decision. Cinematic extreme close-up, warm desk lamp."),
    ("N07", "A diplomatic cable or telegram on a desk: 'THE UNITED KINGDOM REQUESTS CONVERSION OF THREE BILLION DOLLARS IN DOLLAR RESERVES TO GOLD.' The document has official British government letterhead. A senior US Treasury official is reading it with an expression that confirms his worst fears. This is the immediate trigger. Cinematic close-up, 1971 government office, fluorescent light."),
    ("N08", "French President Charles de Gaulle, in a period archival scene circa 1965: de Gaulle in formal French presidential attire at a press conference, pointing at a reporter, his expression imperious. A text overlay reads: 'The Contradiction.' He has spent years shipping gold from Fort Knox to Paris because he could see the math was impossible. Cinematic period portrait, French government press room."),
    ("N09", "A French Navy vessel carrying gold across the Atlantic, circa 1965-1971: a period French naval ship at sea, with a hint of cargo manifest visible showing gold bullion shipment. The ship sails away from the American coastline visible in the background. De Gaulle's systematic gold repatriation made physical. Cinematic wide shot, Atlantic ocean, gray sky, period-accurate naval vessel."),
    ("N10", "Fort Knox exterior, 1971: the massive gold storage facility in Kentucky, its neoclassical exterior visible behind security fencing and guard posts. The building looks impregnable. But inside, the gold reserves have been substantially depleted by a decade of dollar outflows. The gap between the imposing exterior and the diminished interior is the story. Cinematic wide establishing shot, Kentucky countryside, warm summer light."),
    ("N11", "An illustrated graph of declining US gold reserves: a line chart from 1950 to 1971 showing US gold holdings falling from two-thirds of the world's monetary gold at the war's end to substantially diminished reserves by 1971. The line falls steadily. The dollar claims on that gold are shown as a second line rising above it. The gap between the two lines is the crisis. Clean period infographic style."),
    ("N12", "Treasury Secretary John Connally in the Camp David conference room, standing to deliver his recommendation. A large Texan in a period suit, commanding and certain. His expression is aggressive confidence — he is pushing for the boldest move. The other advisers around the table are listening intently. Connally's physicality and certainty dominate the room. Cinematic wide shot, period conference room."),
    ("N13", "A close-up of Connally's hands on the conference table, pointing at the yellow legal pad's top option. His cufflinks catch the light. His expression is decisive. He is recommending: close the gold window entirely, impose import surcharges, announce wage and price controls, seize maximum political initiative in one move. The boldest option. Cinematic close-medium shot, Camp David conference room."),
    ("N14", "Nixon and Connally reviewing the decision together privately, late evening August 14, 1971: Nixon in an open-collared period shirt, Connally in his suit. They stand near a window in the Lodge. Nixon has agreed to the bold option. The decision is made. The world does not know yet. Cinematic medium shot, Camp David Lodge interior, evening window light."),
    ("N15", "The Oval Office or White House television broadcast setup, Sunday August 15, 1971, being prepared for Nixon's address: technicians setting up camera equipment, placing American flags in position, adjusting the desk. The stage being set for an announcement that will change the world monetary system permanently. Cinematic wide shot, period White House interior."),
    ("N16", "Richard Nixon at the podium delivering his August 15, 1971 address to the nation: in a dark period business suit, American flag to his left, looking directly at the camera with practiced presidential calm. He is saying the United States will no longer exchange dollars for gold. No one watching knows what this means yet. Cinematic medium portrait shot, period TV broadcast lighting."),
    ("N17", "A 1971 television set in an American living room broadcasting Nixon's speech: the TV screen shows Nixon's face, the room around it is a 1971 American family's living room — period furniture, shag carpet, a family watching. Their expressions show polite attentive confusion — they don't fully understand what is being announced. Cinematic wide shot, 1971 American domestic interior."),
    ("N18", "The reaction in foreign capitals: a European central bank official watching Nixon's speech on a television in his office in the early morning hours of August 16, 1971. His expression shifts from confusion to alarm as the implications become clear. His phone is already ringing. No consultation. No negotiation. One Sunday night speech. Cinematic medium shot, European government office, TV light in darkness."),
    ("N19", "A French government official on the phone the morning of August 16, 1971: in period business attire, speaking urgently, his face showing controlled fury. Behind him, a television showing a replay of Nixon's address. The French government calling it 'monetary aggression.' Cinematic medium shot, French government office, morning light."),
    ("N20", "John Connally at a press conference being asked how foreign governments will react: in his period suit, leaning slightly forward to the microphone, an expression of complete calm bordering on amusement. He delivers his line: 'The dollar is our currency, but it is your problem.' Cinematic medium close-up, press conference lighting, period setting."),
    ("N21", "A newspaper stand in New York City, August 16, 1971: a newsstand with multiple papers displayed, all with front-page headlines about Nixon's gold announcement. 'DOLLAR NO LONGER TIED TO GOLD.' People in period 1971 clothing stop to look at the headlines. The announcement as historical fact, the public encountering it in real time. Cinematic wide shot, period New York street."),
    ("N22", "A diplomatic document dated August 15, 1971 with the heading 'TEMPORARY SUSPENSION OF GOLD CONVERTIBILITY.' The word 'temporary' is underlined. A legal annotation beside it reads: 'Never reversed.' The contrast between the announced temporary nature and the permanent reality. Cinematic close-up of the document, formal government paper, clean document lighting."),
    ("N23", "A 1973 currency trading floor at a major bank: traders in period clothing watching multiple screens showing floating exchange rates. Currencies are now valued by market forces, not gold. The numbers fluctuate visibly. For the first time in recorded history, no currency is tied to any physical commodity. Cinematic wide shot, 1973 trading floor, fluorescent light, visible urgency."),
    ("N24", "A historical timeline graphic: six monetary anchors across six thousand years. The Lydian electrum coin (620 BCE), the Byzantine solidus (312 CE), the Florentine florin (1252 CE), the classical gold standard (1870s), Bretton Woods (1944), and then — nothing. A gap after 1971. The six thousand year chain of commodity-anchored money ending in one Sunday night speech. Cinematic documentary timeline on dark background, gold accent color."),
    ("N25", "Henry Kissinger in Saudi Arabia, 1974: in a period dark suit, meeting with Saudi government officials in traditional Saudi dress in a formal reception room. The meeting is about the price of oil. Kissinger is offering US military security guarantees. Photorealistic cinematic illustration, formal Saudi government interior, warm afternoon light."),
    ("N26", "The petrodollar deal: a visual of oil tankers in the Persian Gulf flying Saudi and American flags, with currency symbols showing oil transactions denominated in US dollars. The mechanism that replaced the gold anchor — you need dollars to buy oil, so the whole world needs dollars. Cinematic wide shot, Persian Gulf, warm sunset over water."),
    ("N27", "A 1975 OPEC meeting: oil ministers in formal national dress from multiple Middle Eastern and African nations at a conference table in Vienna. A decision board on the wall shows oil prices denominated in US dollars. All OPEC nations pricing in dollars. The gold standard replaced by an oil standard. Cinematic wide shot, formal international conference setting."),
    ("N28", "The power structure unchanged: a symbolic comparison graphic. Left panel: ancient figure controlling the gold mine as the source of monetary power. Right panel: modern figure controlling oil supply as the source of monetary power. Both command the reserve commodity. Control the reserve commodity, control global finance. The mechanism is different; the power relationship is identical. Cinematic split documentary graphic on dark background."),

    # ── s7_modern (M01–M34) ──
    # Narration: gold price 1971-2026 ($35 to $5000+), the price as a signal,
    # 2022 Russian reserve freeze, central banks reacting, gold bars in vaults,
    # gold being moved, central bank purchase data, Poland/India/China buying,
    # dollar's declining reserve share, central banks' risk assessment,
    # the Pactolus River callback, gold never leaving the room.

    ("M01", "A dramatic gold price chart covering 1971 to 2026, displayed on a sleek modern financial screen: the line starts flat at thirty-five dollars per ounce at the left edge of the chart, rises steadily through the 1970s gold boom, dips in the 1980s and 1990s, then rises sharply after 2000, accelerates after 2008, and explodes upward past 2020 toward five thousand dollars at the right edge. The line glows gold against a dark background. Clean cinematic financial data visualization."),
    ("M02", "A close-up of a modern financial terminal screen showing gold spot price at five thousand dollars per ounce, March 2026. The number is large and prominent. Other financial data visible in smaller text around it. The screen's glow illuminates the face of a trader in a modern financial office, his expression reading the number with careful attention. Cinematic close medium shot, modern trading room, screen light dominant."),
    ("M03", "A comparative inflation visual: a dollar bill from 1971 and a dollar bill from 2026, side by side. Under each, a label shows purchasing power: '1971 dollar buys $7.50 in 2026 goods.' But gold went from thirty-five dollars to five thousand — far beyond inflation adjustment. The price signals something more than dollar weakness. Clean documentary graphic on dark background."),
    ("M04", "February 2022: a news broadcast on a large screen in a modern central bank boardroom showing the announcement of the freeze of Russian central bank reserves. The screen shows financial news logos and the headline. Around the conference table, central bank officials in modern business suits are watching. The expressions are serious and calculating — drawing their own conclusions. Cinematic wide shot, modern government institutional interior."),
    ("M05", "A visualization of the Russian reserve freeze mechanism: a world map showing three hundred billion dollars in Russian assets held in Western financial institutions — highlighted locations in the EU, US, and UK — with a lock icon overlaid on each. An executive order document. The mechanism is simple and total: reserves held abroad can be frozen by foreign executive decision. Documentary infographic on dark background, cinematic."),
    ("M06", "A central bank official in a modern suit at his desk studying a classified briefing document. His expression is grave and calculating. On his desk, a large photograph of Russian reserve freeze news coverage. He is drawing the obvious conclusion: our reserves held abroad could face the same outcome. Gold in our own vaults cannot. Cinematic close medium shot, modern government office, window light."),
    ("M07", "A modern central bank gold vault interior: rows of gold bars stacked precisely on metal shelving, gleaming under institutional lighting. The bars are uniform, each stamped with official markings. A vault guard in uniform visible at the far end. The gold is physically in the country's own territory — it cannot be frozen remotely. Cinematic wide shot, modern vault, warm metallic light on the gold surface."),
    ("M08", "Physical gold being moved: uniformed security personnel carefully loading gold bars from a vault onto a reinforced transport vehicle inside a secure facility. Each bar is checked against a manifest. The gold is being physically relocated — perhaps from a foreign depository to domestic storage. Cinematic medium wide shot, secure logistics facility, institutional lighting."),
    ("M09", "A gold bar being examined closely: a uniformed vault official holds a gold bar up to examine its markings — the official stamp, weight, assay number. His expression is careful and professional. Behind him, rows of identical bars extend into the distance. The gold is not a data entry in a foreign database — it is a physical object in a physical room. Cinematic close medium shot, vault interior."),
    ("M10", "A chart showing central bank gold purchases 2010 to 2024: a bar chart with two distinct eras clearly visible — low purchase volumes from 2010-2021, and then dramatically higher bars for 2022, 2023, and 2024, each over one thousand metric tons. The bars for the post-Russia freeze years are more than double the height of the prior decade's average. Clean cinematic documentary graphic, dark background, the acceleration unmistakable."),
    ("M11", "A 2025 central bank survey visualization: a horizontal bar chart showing percentages. The largest bar reads '43% of central banks plan to increase gold holdings in the coming year.' Other bars show neutral and decreasing categories. The forty-three percent majority is highlighted in gold. Documentary infographic graphic on dark background."),
    ("M12", "Poland's central bank gold acquisition, 2024: a formal ceremony in Warsaw where Polish government and National Bank of Poland officials pose with a large gold bar for official photographs. Polish flags in the background. The scene is formal and proud — Poland has added ninety tons of gold in 2024. Photorealistic cinematic illustration of a formal institutional event."),
    ("M13", "India's Reserve Bank gold movement: uniformed security personnel transporting gold in armored vehicles through an Indian city, with official escort. News cameras visible at a distance. India has moved gold home from abroad and added seventy-three tons in 2024. The physical logistics of gold repatriation. Cinematic wide shot, Indian urban setting, daylight."),
    ("M14", "A world map showing gold purchase flows, 2022-2025: arrows pointing from gold markets toward central bank destinations across Eastern Europe, South Asia, and East Asia. Poland, India, and a question-mark labeled 'China' highlighted. The arrows are gold on dark blue, the map communicating the global scope of the buying shift. Cinematic documentary map, dark background."),
    ("M15", "A scene in a modern Chinese central bank facility: officials in business suits reviewing classified documents about gold reserves. The faces are neutral and professional, the atmosphere guarded. China does not disclose its purchases accurately. The secrecy itself is information — the world's largest buyer chooses not to be visible. Cinematic medium wide shot, modern Chinese government institutional interior."),
    ("M16", "A graph showing the dollar's share of global foreign exchange reserves, 2000 to 2025: the line starts above seventy percent in the early two-thousands and declines steadily to approximately fifty-eight percent by 2025. The decline is steady and unmistakable. A second line shows gold's share rising. Two trends moving in opposite directions. Clean documentary graphic on dark background."),
    ("M17", "A central bank economist at a conference table in a modern government building, presenting data to colleagues. A projected chart shows the dollar's declining reserve share. His expression is serious and analytic. The colleagues lean forward studying the data. These are the people who manage the fiat monetary system, and they are looking at its structural pressure. Cinematic wide shot, modern conference room, natural light."),
    ("M18", "A split-image visualization of the fifty-three year fiat monetary experiment timeline: left panel labeled '1971' shows Nixon's speech on a television screen — the start of the experiment. Right panel labeled '2026' shows a modern financial trading floor — the experiment still running, fifty-three years of fiat money, the longest the world has gone without any monetary anchor. Cinematic split documentary graphic."),
    ("M19", "A central bank decision-maker in a private meeting room: a senior official in a modern suit reading a briefing paper titled (partially visible) 'STRATEGIC GOLD RESERVE ASSESSMENT.' His expression is one of carefully measured concern. He is not predicting the end of fiat currency — he is hedging against possibilities he cannot fully see. Cinematic close medium shot, private meeting room, afternoon window light."),
    ("M20", "A visual of the six-thousand-year gold timeline: a long horizontal timeline on a dark wall in a modern strategy room. Markers at: Varna 4400 BCE, Lydia 620 BCE, Constantinople 312 CE, Florence 1252, the Gold Standard 1870s, Bretton Woods 1944, Nixon 1971. A central banker stands before it, hands clasped, studying it. The question visible in his posture: which monetary system was permanent, and which was temporary? Cinematic wide shot."),
    ("M21", "The Pactolus River callback: the Pactolus River in modern Turkey, a small and unremarkable stream near the town of Sart, ancient Sardis. Tourist signage at the bank. The water is clear and shallow, no gold visible to the casual observer. But the central banks of the world are buying what this river once carried. The oldest gold connection in monetary history, still relevant. Cinematic medium wide shot, modern Turkey, afternoon light."),
    ("M22", "A global central bank vault complex, modern era: an underground vault somewhere in Frankfurt, London, or New York — a massive chamber with rows of gold bar pallets extending far into the distance. The scale communicates strategic reserve, not investment portfolio. This is a hedge — the physical kind that cannot be frozen by any foreign government. Cinematic ultra-wide shot, modern vault lighting."),
    ("M23", "A conceptual image of 'the signal in the data': a modern analyst's desk with multiple screens showing central bank gold purchase data, the Russian reserve freeze news, dollar reserve share decline charts. The analyst connects the data points with red string on a pinboard beside the screens. The pattern is clear when you see all three together. Cinematic medium wide shot, modern office, screen light and desk lamp."),
    ("M24", "An official statement being printed: a document headed 'CENTRAL BANK GOLD PURCHASE REPORT Q4 2024' showing acquisition data for multiple countries. The numbers are large. The document is unremarkable in format — routine official reporting of extraordinary activity. Cinematic close-up of the document, warm desk lamp, the routine bureaucratic language reporting an historic trend."),
    ("M25", "A side-by-side portrait comparison: on the left, a 1971 era US Treasury official in period suit and wide tie — the man who ended the gold standard. On the right, a 2024 era central bank official in modern suit examining a gold bar in a vault. Both men are part of the same institution. One closed the gold window. The other is buying gold at the fastest rate in fifty years. Cinematic split portrait, period versus modern lighting."),
    ("M26", "A close-up of a gold bar's official stamp: the assay number, weight (400 troy ounces), purity (999.9 fine), and the seal of a major central bank. The bar is held in gloved hands. Every marking on this bar — the weight, the purity, the official stamp — connects directly back to the first stamp pressed into electrum in Lydia. The architecture is the same. Extreme macro photography, warm studio light."),
    ("M27", "The Florentine florin callback: a close-up of a period florin coin beside a modern gold bar, both on black velvet. The florin is three and a half grams of pure gold from 1252. The gold bar is four hundred troy ounces from 2024. The metal is the same; the monetary function has officially ended for both. But both are being held as reserves. Documentary macro photography, warm amber studio light."),
    ("M28", "A world map at night from satellite altitude: lights of major cities visible against the dark planet. In specific cities — Warsaw, Mumbai, Beijing, Ankara, Cairo, Riyadh — small gold icons mark central bank gold storage facilities. The gold is scattered across the physical globe, in sovereign custody, immune to remote action. Cinematic dark globe visualization, gold accent icons."),
    ("M29", "A modern finance ministry official being briefed by an economist: the official in a dark suit listens as the economist presents data on a tablet screen. The tablet shows gold prices and purchase volumes. The official's expression is one of careful attention. They are not fringe economists or gold bugs — they are the mainstream institutional actors hedging against the mainstream system. Cinematic medium shot, modern government interior."),
    ("M30", "The fiat monetary experiment in numbers: a clean documentary graphic showing '53 YEARS — THE LONGEST THE WORLD HAS OPERATED WITHOUT A MONETARY ANCHOR.' Below it, the previous records: Bretton Woods 27 years, the classical gold standard 44 years. The current experiment is already the longest. The number is the question. Dark background, cinematic graphic, gold typography."),
    ("M31", "The purchasing behavior versus the official narrative: a split image. Left panel shows a central banker at a podium defending the fiat system in public — a press conference, formal, confident. Right panel shows the same institution's gold purchase data as a bar chart, surging upward. The official narrative and the actual behavior pointing in different directions. Cinematic split documentary graphic."),
    ("M32", "A wide shot of a modern financial district at dusk — Frankfurt, London, or New York. Glass towers reflecting the sky, the machinery of fiat finance operating at global scale. From above, the district looks powerful and permanent. But in the vaults beneath some of these buildings, gold is accumulating at a rate not seen in fifty years. The system hedging against itself. Cinematic ultra-wide shot, blue-hour financial district light."),
    ("M33", "The Pactolus River one more time: this time looking upstream from a low angle, the water moving toward the camera over smooth river stones. In the far distance, the hills of western Turkey. The river that started six thousand years of gold money still flows. The central banks buying gold are reaching back along the same thread that started here. Cinematic low-angle medium shot, natural Turkish landscape, afternoon light."),
    ("M34", "The final visual for the modern section: a modern gold bar in the center of the frame on black velvet, studio-lit to emphasize the warm metallic surface. Around it in a circle, eight small images of historical gold coins — Lydian electrum, Byzantine solidus, Florentine florin, Spanish doubloon, and others. The gold bar in the center connected to all of them. The metal never really left. Documentary composite photograph, warm amber studio lighting."),

    # ── s8_close (X01–X29) ──
    # Narration: every monetary system feels permanent, Byzantine debasement,
    # gold standard's 44 years, Nixon ending Bretton Woods in a weekend,
    # chemistry not a choice, everything else was a choice — mint control,
    # rule setting, debt protection, Potosi workers, Camp David decision-makers,
    # monetary systems as political choices, fiat system's beneficiaries,
    # central bank gold hedging, the experiment still running, gold's journey,
    # gold never leaving the room, the viewer takeaway.

    ("X01", "A wide shot of a Roman marketplace at the height of the Empire, circa 100 CE: prosperous stalls, bright gold solidi changing hands, citizens in confident Roman dress. The monetary system looks permanent and stable. No one in this scene believes it will collapse within two centuries. Cinematic wide shot, Roman market, warm midday Mediterranean light — the false permanence of a thriving system."),
    ("X02", "The Byzantine solidus in its prime: a coin on black velvet, perfectly struck, full weight, brilliant gold surface. A label below reads '312 CE — 700 years of stability begins.' The coin is the visual anchor for an era of monetary certainty that its users could not imagine ending. Museum macro photography, warm studio lighting."),
    ("X03", "Byzantine coinage debasement: a single gold solidus that has been debased — slightly thinner, slightly less gold-colored, the emperor's portrait slightly less precise. It sits beside an older solidus of full weight and purity. The change happened in a single generation. The seven-century standard that felt permanent, breaking. Cinematic macro comparison on dark velvet, museum lighting."),
    ("X04", "The gold standard of the 1870s being celebrated: a political illustration from the period showing politicians and bankers raising glasses in a formal dinner setting, surrounded by imagery of gold coins and stability. A banner reads 'THE PERMANENT ACHIEVEMENT OF CIVILIZATION.' Forty-four years later it will be gone. Cinematic period illustration, warm Victorian dining room, formal gas lighting."),
    ("X05", "The gold standard at its end, 1914: a formal bank announcement board being changed from 'GOLD CONVERTIBLE' to 'GOLD PAYMENTS SUSPENDED — WAR EMERGENCY.' A small crowd reads the announcement. The permanent achievement of civilization, ended in days by the reality of industrial warfare. Cinematic medium shot, period European bank exterior."),
    ("X06", "The Bretton Woods conference, 1944: the great ballroom of the Mount Washington Hotel in New Hampshire, hundreds of delegates from 44 nations seated at long tables. They are designing the postwar world monetary system. The atmosphere is confident and historic. They believe they are building something permanent. Cinematic wide shot, formal conference hall, 1944 period dress."),
    ("X07", "Nixon's speech, August 15, 1971: the same image as N16 but now seen from a greater distance — Nixon small in the frame, the television set in the living room small, the house small in its neighborhood. The perspective communicates how a decision by a few people in one weekend restructured the monetary system for the entire world. Cinematic wide establishing shot, diminishing scale from TV broadcast to house exterior."),
    ("X08", "A timeline of monetary system durations on a dark background: the Byzantine solidus (700 years), the Florentine florin (281 years), the classical gold standard (44 years), Bretton Woods (27 years), and the current fiat system (53 years and counting) — each shown as a horizontal bar of proportional length. The fiat bar is labeled 'Still running.' The pattern is clear: each system felt permanent to those inside it. Cinematic documentary timeline graphic."),
    ("X09", "A close-up of a gold nugget in a river, natural and unreacted — the pure element that chemistry selected. No human hand has touched it. No government has stamped it. The chemistry chose this before humans did. That part was not a choice. Wide-angle extreme close-up, natural river light, photorealistic, the gold glinting in flowing water."),
    ("X10", "The first stamp: a craftsman's hand pressing a lion-head die into electrum in an ancient Lydian workshop. The die being struck with a hammer, the metal receiving the impression. This was a choice — who controlled the mint, who issued the guarantee, who set the terms. Cinematic close-up, forge light, the moment of human choice layered onto chemical necessity."),
    ("X11", "Who controlled the mint: King Croesus in his Lydian palace receiving a report from his chief mint official. The king examines a gold Croeseid. He controls the metal, the stamp, and the guarantee. The mint is a political instrument. Cinematic medium shot, ancient Lydian royal interior, oil lamp warmth."),
    ("X12", "Who set the rules: a wide shot of the 1870s British Parliament chamber during a debate on the gold standard. The chamber is full, the argument heated. Men in Victorian frock coats gesture and argue. The rules about who is protected by deflation and who is exposed — these were made in rooms like this. Cinematic historical illustration, Victorian parliamentary setting."),
    ("X13", "Whose debts were protected: the 1890s American creditor in his comfortable office again, reviewing his gold-backed bonds with satisfaction. And simultaneously — through a window visible behind him — the prairie farm and the indebted farmer in the distance. The same system, two different positions, by design. Cinematic medium shot with background window, warm office interior contrasting with cold prairie light."),
    ("X14", "Whose debts were doubled: the 1890s American farmer at his kitchen table at night with the mortgage document and the wheat price chart. The same scene as before but now seen as a consequence of the design, not an accident. His real debt doubled not because anyone changed the contract but because the system was built to work this way. Cinematic close-medium shot, candlelight, farmhouse."),
    ("X15", "Who descended the shaft: an indigenous mitayo worker at the entrance to Cerro Rico, the tallow candle on his forehead, the shaft descending into darkness behind him. He did not make the decision that the mine would operate this way. He did not choose the mita. The system reached into his life from above and took him. Cinematic close portrait, cold Andean dawn light, the darkness of the shaft behind him."),
    ("X16", "The contrast: Camp David decision-makers versus Cerro Rico workers. A split image. Left panel: Nixon and Connally at the Camp David conference table in summer 1971, comfortable, powerful, making history. Right panel: an indigenous mitayo worker descending the Potosi mine shaft in 1590, in darkness, carrying ore. Both are actors in monetary systems. One makes the choices. One carries the weight. Cinematic triptych, dramatic period-accurate illustration."),
    ("X17", "The political choice dressed as natural fact: a dramatic symbolic image. A large gold coin hangs against a dark background, but behind it — barely visible — are strings attached to it going upward out of frame, like a puppet. The coin appears to float naturally. The strings are the political choices invisible to most people. Cinematic symbolic illustration, dark background, dramatic backlighting."),
    ("X18", "The gold standard as a class structure: a wide social panorama from the 1890s. At the top, creditors in top hats reviewing bond portfolios in banks. In the middle, factory workers receiving wages in gold-backed currency. At the bottom, farmers with declining income and fixed debt. The three levels visible simultaneously in a single wide-angle historical scene. Cinematic documentary illustration, warm period lighting."),
    ("X19", "The fiat system's beneficiaries: a modern equivalent scene. At the top, institutions with access to cheap capital and Federal Reserve programs. In the middle, wage workers whose wages adjust slowly to inflation. At the bottom, those with fixed incomes and high-interest debt. Different era, same three-level structure. The fiat system also has beneficiaries. Clean cinematic modern illustration, parallel composition to X18."),
